title: A Phase 2a Multicenter, Randomized, Double-Blind, Parallel Group, 26-Week, Placebo-Controlled Study of SUVN-502 in Subjects With Moderate Alzheimer's Disease Currently Treated With Donepezil Hydrochloride and Memantine Hydrochloride
description_brief: This is a phase 2a, proof-of-concept, 26-week, double-blind, multicenter, randomized, parallel group, placebo-controlled study to compare the efficacy and safety of treatment with SUVN-502 to placebo treatment in subjects with moderate Alzheimer's disease receiving stable doses of donepezil HCl and memantine HCl.
description_detailed:
This is a phase 2a, proof-of-concept, 26-week, double-blind, multicenter, randomized, parallel group, placebo-controlled study to compare the efficacy and safety of treatment with SUVN-502 to placebo treatment in subjects with moderate Alzheimer's disease receiving donepezil HCl (10 mg qd) and either memantine HCl (10 mg twice daily \[bid\]) or Namenda XR® (Extended Release, 28 mg qd) or the combination therapy, Namzaric™

The primary objective of the study is to evaluate the efficacy of a serotonin receptor subtype 6 (5-HT6) antagonist, SUVN-502, compared to placebo, as adjunct treatment in subjects with moderate Alzheimer's disease (Mini-Mental State Examination \[MMSE\] score of 12 to 20) currently treated with the acetylcholinesterase inhibitor, donepezil hydrochloride (HCl), and the N-methyl-D-aspartic acid (NMDA) antagonist, memantine HCl. Efficacy will be assessed by the 11-item Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale for Cognitive Behavior (ADAScog-11) after 26 weeks of treatment.

measures.title: Mini-Mental State Examination
measures.description: Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE) was used to measure cognitive impairment. The MMSE can evaluate overall cognitive function, and is widely used for the assessment of cognitive impairment in dementia patients. The questionnaire consists of 11 items, and each item aims to evaluate different cognitive domains such as orientation, memory, attention, and construction. The score ranged from 0 to 30, with a higher score indicating better function.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to Week-26 in Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale-Cognitive Subscale 11 (ADAS-Cog 11)
outcomeMeasures.description: Mean change from baseline at week 26 is assessed for ADAS-Cog11 score. The ADAS-Cog11 is a structured scale that evaluates memory, orientation, attention, reasoning, language, and constructional praxis. ADAS-Cog11 measures cognition by assessing 11 metrics impaired in AD: word recall; commands; constructional praxis; naming objects and fingers; ideational praxis; orientation; word recognition; remembering test instructions; spoken language ability; word-finding difficulty; and comprehension of spoken language. The scale ranges from 0 to 70, with higher scores indicate greater impairment.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to Week-26 in Clinical Dementia Rating Scale - Sum of Boxes (CDR-SB)
outcomeMeasures.description:
Clinical Dementia Rating-Sum of Boxes (CDR-SB) - Sum of Boxes CDR-SB is a semi-structured interview of participants and their caregivers. Participant's cognitive status is rated across 6 domains of functioning, including memory, orientation, judgment/problem solving, community affairs, home/hobbies, and personal care.

Severity score assigned for each of 6 domains; total score (SB) ranges from 0 to 18. Higher scores indicate greater disease severity.

The ADCS-ADL measures both basic and instrumental activities of daily living The total ADCS-ADL score ranges from 0 to 78, with lower scores indicating greater disease severity.

drug: SUVN-502 (masupirdine) — selective 5‑HT6 (serotonin 6) receptor antagonist; orally active small molecule
explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests SUVN‑502 as an adjunct to donepezil + memantine with the primary efficacy endpoint ADAS‑Cog‑11 (cognitive measure), indicating the intervention aims to improve cognition rather than target amyloid/tau pathology. citeturn0search0turn0search1.

Act: Web search identifies SUVN‑502 as masupirdine, a selective 5‑HT6 receptor antagonist developed as an orally‑active small molecule evaluated for cognitive deficits in AD (phase 2 described). The phase‑2 study randomized ~564 patients to masupirdine 50 mg, 100 mg, or placebo and used ADAS‑Cog as primary outcome. citeturn0search0turn0search4.

Act (additional evidence): Preclinical and phase‑1 data characterize SUVN‑502/masupirdine as a small molecule with CNS penetration that modulates cholinergic/monoaminergic neurotransmission to enhance cognition; later analyses also noted potential effects on agitation in subgroup/post‑hoc analyses, but the trial in question was designed and powered for cognitive outcome. citeturn0search7turn0search5.

Reflect: Given the mechanism (5‑HT6 antagonism) and trial endpoints (ADAS‑Cog), the correct category is 'cognitive enhancer' — not a disease‑targeted biologic (no antibody/vaccine) nor a disease‑targeted small molecule acting on amyloid/tau, and although there is signal for neuropsychiatric symptom improvement in post‑hoc analyses, the primary intent in this trial was cognitive enhancement. citeturn0search1turn0search5.
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational drug SUVN-502 (masupirdine) is a selective 5‑HT6 (serotonin 6) receptor antagonist being tested as an adjunctive cognitive enhancer in AD—5‑HT6 is a neurotransmitter G‑protein coupled receptor, so the intervention targets a neurotransmitter receptor pathway. citeturn0search0turn0search4

Act: Extracted trial details — masupirdine (SUVN‑502) is an orally active, selective 5‑HT6 receptor antagonist; the described study was a randomized, double‑blind, placebo‑controlled Phase 2 (26‑week) trial in moderate AD on background donepezil+memantine with ADAS‑Cog‑11 as the primary efficacy endpoint (≈564 randomized patients, masupirdine 50 mg and 100 mg vs placebo). These facts come from the phase‑2 reports and trial publications. citeturn0search0turn0search2

Act (additional evidence): Preclinical and other analyses report pro‑cognitive effects and modulation of cholinergic/monoaminergic neurotransmission and possible effects on agitation/aggression in models and post‑hoc clinical analyses, supporting a neurotransmitter‑receptor (symptomatic cognitive/behavioral) mechanism rather than an amyloid/tau disease‑modifying mechanism. citeturn0search5turn0search3

Reflect: Given the explicit 5‑HT6 receptor mechanism and the symptomatic cognitive endpoint (ADAS‑Cog) rather than targeting amyloid, tau, ApoE, inflammation, etc., the correct CADRO classification is D) Neurotransmitter Receptors. The trial is symptomatic (cognitive enhancer) and not a multi‑target or non‑therapeutic intervention, so 'D) Neurotransmitter Receptors' best fits.
